title: Metabolome and exposome profiling of the biospecimens from COVID-19 patients in India (Blood plasma assay)
description:
INTRODUCTION: COVID-19 has become a global impediment by bringing everything to a halt starting from January 2020. India underwent the lockdown starting from 22nd March 2020 with the sudden spike in the number of COVID-19 patients in major cities and states. This study focused on how metabolites play a crucial role in SARSCoV-2 prognosis.

MATERIALS AND METHODS: Metabolome profiling of 106 plasma samples and 24 swab samples from symptomatic patients in the Indian population of the Mumbai region was done. COVID-19 positive samples were further segregated under the non-severe COVID-19 and severe COVID-19 patient cohort for both plasma and swab.

RESULTS: After analyzing the raw files, total 7,949 and 12,871 metabolites in plasma and swab were found. 11 and 35 significantly altered metabolites were found in COVID-19 positive compared to COVID-19 negative plasma and swab samples, respectively. Also, 9 and 23 significantly altered metabolites were found in severe COVID-19 positive to non-severe COVID-19 positive plasma and swab samples, respectively. The majorly affected pathways in COVID-19 patients were found to be the amino acid metabolism pathway, sphingosine metabolism pathway, and bile salt metabolism pathway.

CONCLUSION: This study facilitates identification of potential metabolite-based biomarker candidates for rapid diagnosis and prognosis for clinical applications.


Blood plasma assay is reported in the current study MTBLS2291.

Nasopharyngeal swab assay is reported in MTBLS2349.

publications.title: Metabolome and exposome profiling of the biospecimens from COVID-19 patients in India

protocols.name: Chromatography
protocols.description: The extracted samples containing internal standard were analyzed using Ultraperformance Liquid Chromatography-High-Resolution Mass Spectrometry (UPLC-HRMS) methods involving a Thermo Scientific Dionex UltiMate 3000 System coupled to a Q Exactive mass spectrometer. The capillary, probe, autosampler and column temperatures were 340, 380, 4 and 40 °C, respectively. A C18 column, i.e., Hypersil GOLD (100 x 2.1 mm, 1.9 µm particle size, Thermo Fisher Scientific, USA), was used for metabolite separation using water and 100% methanol as eluents both with 0.1% formic acid added, in a gradient lasting 20 min. The gradient consecutively reached 1% of methanol at 2 min, 50% methanol at 5 min, 98% methanol at 14 min, constant at 98% until 17 min, 1% at 17.2 min, and constant at 1% methanol until 20 min with a flow rate of 0.350 ml/min.

protocols.name: Extraction
protocols.description: The tubes were incubated in a bio-safety cabinet for 1.5 h until ethanol was evaporated. To the semi-dried sample, 4x (400 μl) absolute methanol was added and vortexed briefly. The tube was incubated at -20 °C overnight. The next day, the sample was centrifuged at 4 °C for 30 min at 12,000 x g. The supernatant was collected in a fresh tube and stored at -20 °C. Samples were transported at 4 °C to the Proteomics Lab, IIT Bombay. A total of 250 μl of the supernatant was concentrated using a SpeedVac up to a final volume of approximately 80 μl. 50 μl of the concentrated sample was dispensed in the glass vial for the MS-based metabolomic profile run. To each glass vial containing 50 μl of the metabolite extract, 0.5 μl of reserpine (10 μg/ml) was added as an internal control for capturing instrumental variation. Vials containing metabolite extract were then placed in an autosampler for metabolite profiling.

protocols.name: Mass spectrometry
protocols.description:
Mass spectra data were collected on a Thermo Scientific Q Exactive mass spectrometer in Electrospray Ionization (ESI) positive mode. Each sample was run in triplicates, where one run was set for MS/MS analysis for identification of the metabolites. The rest 2 runs for each sample were used as technical replicates for acquiring MS data of extracted metabolites. The resolution of the mass spectrometer was set at 140,000 for full MS and 17,500 for ddMS2 and scanned at a mass range 100-700 m/z. Sheath Gas flow rate at 42, Aux Gas rate at 10, and spray voltage at 3.8 kV.


The samples were run in batches, and each sample was analyzed in 3 technical replicates using MS only and MS2 modes. Each batch of samples had initial blank runs consisting of 50% methanol, and a single blank was run after every sample. QC control samples consisting of a pool of samples were also run after every 5 samples to check the consistency of the instrument performance.
